# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: flux-cd
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:flux-cd/cloud-native-computing-foundation] The **Cloud Native Computing Foundation** (**CNCF**) is a subsidiary of the Linux Foundation founded in 2015 to support cloud-native computing.
[src:flux-cd/cloud-native-computing-foundation] It was announced alongside Kubernetes 1.0, an open source container cluster manager, which was contributed to the Linux Foundation by Google as a seed technology.
[src:flux-cd/cloud-native-computing-foundation] Founding members include Google, CoreOS, Mesosphere, Red Hat, Twitter, Huawei, Intel, RX-M, Cisco, IBM, Docker, Univa, and VMware.
[src:flux-cd/cloud-native-computing-foundation] Today, CNCF is supported by over 450 members.
[src:flux-cd/cloud-native-computing-foundation] In August 2018 Google announced that it was handing over operational control of Kubernetes to the community.
[src:flux-cd/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment contrasts with *continuous delivery* (also abbreviated CD), a similar approach in which software functionalities are also frequently delivered and deemed to be potentially capable of being deployed, but are actually not deployed.
[src:flux-cd/continuous-deployment] As such, continuous deployment can be viewed as a more complete form of automation than continuous delivery.
[src:flux-cd/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment has been adopted by software companies such as Meta, Microsoft, Atlassian, IBM, Adobe, and Tesla.
[src:flux-cd/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment extends the principles of continuous integration and delivery by including fully automated production deployment without the need for manual approval, instead relying on rigorous automated testing.
[src:flux-cd/continuous-deployment] Reviews may still take place in the form developer-developer code reviews, but the need for intermediary reviewers such as a change-advisory board is minimized.
[src:flux-cd/continuous-deployment] Because code changes are deployed automatically, continuous deployment requires a much higher standard of automated testing, as test quality determines the reliability of releases.
[src:flux-cd/continuous-deployment] Without this, the risk of introducing production failures outweighs the benefits of deployment automation.
[src:flux-cd/continuous-deployment] In addition, continuous deployment emphasizes small incremental changes and dark launches through the use of feature toggles.
[src:flux-cd/continuous-deployment] Developers can deploy code into production months before a public release by gradually adding functionality in small chunks, verifying stability, and then enabling the feature for users when it is considered ready.
[src:flux-cd/continuous-deployment] Continuous deployment removes the need to wait for releases, as once a change passes internal testing it is automatically deployed to production.
[src:flux-cd/continuous-deployment] This allows for shorter time-to-market and more frequent releases, which in turn increases customer satisfaction and provides companies with more marketing opportunities.
[src:flux-cd/continuous-deployment] A major motivation for continuous deployment is that deploying software into the field more often makes it easier to find, catch, and fix bugs.
[src:flux-cd/continuous-deployment] Deploying small, incremental changes makes it easier to trace the origin of bugs, since issues will be isolated to a recent and relatively small code change.
[src:flux-cd/continuous-deployment] Under this methodology, new software features can be released to customers more quickly and frequently after their development, accelerating the delivery of value to customers and enhancing customer satisfaction.
[src:flux-cd/continuous-deployment] Teams can begin to collect customer feedback almost immediately, driving rapid innovation of relevant features.
[src:flux-cd/continuous-deployment] Continuous delivery requires a significant investment in adequate test coverage, real-time monitoring, and strong continuous integration pipelines to prevent bugs from reaching production.
[src:flux-cd/continuous-deployment] Customers may also find software that is constantly changing creates a learning curve which can negatively affect their experience.
[src:flux-cd/continuous-deployment] Moving to continuous delivery is also a culture shift for developers who are accustomed to traditional release cycles, often requiring a proven DevOps process.
[src:flux-cd/continuous-deployment] Adopting this process requires collaboration among multiple stakeholders, including development teams, leadership, operations, and quality assurance.
[src:flux-cd/continuous-deployment] In an environment in which data-centric microservices provide the functionality, and where the microservices can have multiple instances, continuous deployment consists of instantiating the new version of a microservice and retiring the old version once it has drained all the requests in flight.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Although debated, DevOps is generally characterized by three key principles: shared ownership, workflow automation, and rapid feedback.
[src:flux-cd/devops] However, the term is used in multiple contexts.
[src:flux-cd/devops] At its most successful, DevOps is a combination of specific practices, culture change, and tools.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Proposals to combine software development methodologies with deployment and operations concepts first appeared in the late 80s and early 90s.
[src:flux-cd/devops] In 2009, the first DevOps Days conference was held in Ghent, Belgium.
[src:flux-cd/devops] The conference was founded by Belgian IT consultant and practitioner Patrick Debois.
[src:flux-cd/devops] The conference has now spread to other countries.
[src:flux-cd/devops] In 2012, the first "State of DevOps" report was published by Alanna Brown at Puppet Labs.
[src:flux-cd/devops] In 2016, the DORA metrics for throughput (deployment frequency, lead time for changes), and stability (mean time to recover, change failure rate) were published in that year's State of DevOps report.
[src:flux-cd/devops] However, the research methodology and metrics were criticized by some experts.
[src:flux-cd/devops] In response to these criticisms, the 2023 State of DevOps report published changes that updated the stability metric "mean time to recover" to "failed deployment recovery time" acknowledging the confusion the previous metric had caused.
[src:flux-cd/devops] The 2024 report restructured the metrics framework by moving failed deployment recovery time from stability to throughput and introducing a new "rework rate" metric measuring the proportion of unplanned deployments made to fix user-visible issues.
[src:flux-cd/devops] In 2025, DORA moved away from sorting teams into performance tiers and instead introduced seven team archetypes that combine delivery metrics with human factors like burnout, friction, and perceived value.
[src:flux-cd/devops] DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) has developed a set of metrics which are intended to measure software development efficiency and reliability.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Many of the ideas fundamental to DevOps are similar to other well-known practices, such as Lean and Deming's Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle, The Toyota Way, and the Agile approach of breaking down components and batch sizes.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Contrary to the "top-down" prescriptive approach and rigid framework of ITIL in the 1990s, DevOps is "bottom-up" and flexible, having been created by software engineers for their own needs.
[src:flux-cd/devops] The motivations for what has become modern DevOps and several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, continuous integration, and continuous delivery originated in the Agile world, which informally dates to the 1990s and formally to 2001.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Agile development teams using methods such as extreme programming couldn't "satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software" unless they took responsibility for operations and infrastructure for their applications, automating much of that work.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Because Scrum emerged as the dominant Agile framework in the early 2000s and it omitted the engineering practices that were part of many Agile teams, the momentum to automate operations and infrastructure functions splintered from Agile and expanded into what has become modern DevOps.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Today, DevOps focuses on deploying methodology-agnostic, developed software.
[src:flux-cd/devops] ArchOps starts from software architecture artifacts instead of source code for operational deployment, as opposed to DevOps.
[src:flux-cd/devops] ArchOps holds that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.
[src:flux-cd/devops] CI/CD is as critical to DevOps success as automation.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Additionally, improved collaboration and communication between and within teams helps them achieve faster time to market with reduced risks.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Database DevOps applies DevOps and CI/CD principles directly to database development and operations.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Integrating schema changes, migrations, reference data, and other data-layer updates into the same version-controlled and automated pipelines used for application code enables more reliable deployments.
[src:flux-cd/devops] This approach also enables improved coordination between application and data changes.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Typical database DevOps practices include placing database schema definitions under version control, applying automated tests (such as unit tests or migration validation) to database changes, and deploying those changes through CI/CD pipelines.
[src:flux-cd/devops] These practices reduce what is commonly referred to as "schema drift" between development and production systems and lower the risk of deployment failures.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Mobile DevOps is a methodology that applies DevOps' principles to the development of mobile applications.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Traditional DevOps focuses on streamlining the general software development process, but mobile development has unique challenges that require a tailored approach.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Mobile DevOps is not simply a branch of DevOps specific to mobile app development, but rather an extension and reinterpretation of the DevOps philosophy tailored to mobile's specific requirements.
[src:flux-cd/devops] In 2003, Google developed site reliability engineering (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale, high-availability systems while maintaining a high-quality end-user experience.
[src:flux-cd/devops] While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Some of the original authors of the discipline consider SRE as an implementation of DevOps.
[src:flux-cd/devops] The Toyota Production System (TPS), inspired lean thinking with its focus on continuous improvement, kaizen, flow, and small batches.
[src:flux-cd/devops] The andon cord principle of creating fast feedback, swarming, and solving problems stems from TPS.
[src:flux-cd/devops] As its name implies, DevSecOps integrates DevOps within security practices.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Contrary to a traditional centralized security team model, each delivery team is empowered to factor the correct security controls into their software delivery.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Teams perform tests and implement security practices earlier in the development lifecycle, hence the term "shift left".
[src:flux-cd/devops] Security is tested in three main areas: static, software composition, and dynamic.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Checking software statically via static application security testing (SAST) is white-box testing with special focus on security.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Depending on the programming language, different tools are needed to do such static code analysis.
[src:flux-cd/devops] The software composition is analyzed, especially libraries, and the version of each component is checked against vulnerability lists published by CERT and other expert groups.
[src:flux-cd/devops] When giving software to clients, library licenses and their match to the license of the software distributed are in focus, especially copyleft licenses.
[src:flux-cd/devops] In dynamic testing, also called black-box testing, software is tested without knowing its inner functions.
[src:flux-cd/devops] In DevSecOps this practice may be referred to as dynamic application security testing (DAST) or penetration testing.
[src:flux-cd/devops] The goal is early detection of defects including cross-site scripting and SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Often, detected defects from static and dynamic testing are triaged and categorized under taxonomies like the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), maintained by the Mitre Corporation.
[src:flux-cd/devops] This facilitates the prioritization of security bug fixes and also allows frequently recurring weaknesses to be fixed with recommended mitigations.
[src:flux-cd/devops] As of 2025, CWE maintained its own list of frequently-occurring weaknesses, the CWE Top 25.
[src:flux-cd/devops] In addition, organizations like Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) maintain lists of industry-wide frequently recurring software weaknesses.
[src:flux-cd/devops] DevSecOps has also been described as a cultural shift involving a holistic approach to producing secure software by integrating security education, security by design, and security automation.
[src:flux-cd/devops] DevOps initiatives can change how a company's operations, developers, and testers collaborate during development and delivery processes.
[src:flux-cd/devops] DevOps attempts to support consistency, reliability, and efficiency within an organization.
[src:flux-cd/devops] This is usually enabled by a shared code repository or version control.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Many organizations use version control to facilitate DevOps automation technologies like virtual machines, containerization (or OS-level virtualization), and CI/CD, with the Git version control system and the GitHub platform referenced as examples.
[src:flux-cd/devops] It takes its name from the popular version control system Git, and the specific state of deployment configuration is also version-controlled.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Configuration changes can be managed using code review practices, and can be rolled back using version-controlling.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Essentially, all of the changes to a code are tracked, bookmarked, and making any updates to the history can be made easier.
[src:flux-cd/devops] DataOps incorporates the Agile methodology to shorten the cycle time of analytics development in alignment with business goals.
[src:flux-cd/devops] DevOps focuses on continuous delivery by leveraging on-demand IT resources and by automating test and deployment of software.
[src:flux-cd/devops] This merging of software *development* and IT *operations* has improved velocity, quality, predictability and scale of software engineering and deployment.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Borrowing methods from DevOps, DataOps seeks to bring these same improvements to data analytics.
[src:flux-cd/devops] DataOps utilizes statistical process control (SPC) to monitor and control the data analytics pipeline.
[src:flux-cd/devops] With SPC in place, the data flowing through an operational system is constantly monitored and verified.
[src:flux-cd/devops] If an anomaly occurs, the data analytics team can be notified with an automated alert.
[src:flux-cd/devops] DataOps is not tied to a particular technology, architecture, tool, language or framework.
[src:flux-cd/devops] The best DataOps tools promote collaboration, orchestration, quality, security, access and ease of use.
[src:flux-cd/devops] DataOps was first introduced by InformationWeek contributing editor Lenny Liebmann in a blog post on the IBM Big Data & Analytics Hub titled "3 reasons why DataOps is essential for big data success" on June 19, 2014.
[src:flux-cd/devops] The term DataOps was later popularized by Andy Palmer of Tamr and Steph Locke.
[src:flux-cd/devops] DataOps is a moniker for "Data Operations." 2017 was a significant year for DataOps, with significant ecosystem development, analyst coverage, increased keyword searches, surveys, publications, and open source projects.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Gartner placed DataOps on the Hype Cycle for Data Management in 2018.
[src:flux-cd/devops] The total world data volume is forecast to grow at a rate of 32% CAGR to 180 Zettabytes by 2025 (Source: IDC).
[src:flux-cd/devops] DataOps seeks to provide the tools, processes, and organizational structures to accommodate this significant increase in data.
[src:flux-cd/devops] Automation streamlines data preboarding, ingestion, and the management of large integrated databases, freeing the data team to develop new analytics in a more efficient and effective way.
[src:flux-cd/devops] DataOps seeks to increase velocity, reliability, and quality of data analytics.
[src:flux-cd/devops] It emphasizes communication, collaboration, integration, automation, measurement and cooperation between data scientists, analysts, data/ETL (extract, transform, load) engineers, information technology (IT), and quality assurance/governance.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] In the Gitless GitOps model, the Flux controllers are fully decoupled from Git, relying solely on container registries as the source of truth for the desired state of Kubernetes clusters.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] From a user perspective, Git remains the primary interface for managing the desired state, but the underlying implementation leverages OCI-compliant registries to store and distribute the configuration artifacts.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] This approach allows for greater flexibility and scalability, the Git server is no longer a production dependency, while the OCI registry becomes the unified source of truth for all configuration artifacts, SBOMs, cryptographic signatures, and app images.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] In Flux, *GitOps Toolkit* refers to a collection of specialized tools, Flux Controllers, composable APIs, and reusable Go packages available under the fluxcd GitHub organization.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] These components are designed for the purpose of constructing Continuous Delivery workflows on Kubernetes using GitOps principles.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] The GitOps Toolkit serves as the foundation for managing and automating the deployment and configuration of applications and infrastructure within a Kubernetes cluster, promoting a declarative and version-controlled approach to operations.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] For more information, take a look at GitOps Toolkit components.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] The `Kustomization` custom resource represents a local set of Kubernetes resources (e.g. kustomize overlay) that Flux is supposed to reconcile in the cluster.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] The reconciliation runs every five minutes by default, but this can be changed with `.spec.interval`.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] If you make any changes to the cluster using `kubectl edit/patch/delete`, they will be promptly reverted.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] You either suspend the reconciliation or push your changes to a Git repository.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] For more information, take a look at the Kustomize FAQ and the Kustomization CRD.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] The process of installing the Flux components in a GitOps manner is called a *bootstrap*.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] The manifests are applied to the cluster, a `GitRepository` and `Kustomization` are created for the Flux components, then the manifests are pushed to an existing Git repository (or a new one is created).
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] Flux can manage itself just as it manages other resources.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] The bootstrap is done using the `flux` CLI or using our Terraform Provider.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] For more information, take a look at the bootstrap documentation.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] For more information, take a look at continuous delivery as defined in the CNCF.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] For more information, take a look at continuous delivery as defined in the CNCF Glossary.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] Developers can use techniques like feature flags, canary releases, and A/B testing to minimize the chances of introducing bugs or errors that could harm users or interrupt business operations.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] These strategies enable a controlled and gradual rollout of new features, ensuring a smooth and successful release that enhances user trust and improves the overall user experience.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] The Flux project offers a specialised controller called Flagger that implements various progressive delivery techniques.
[src:flux-cd/flux-concepts] For more information, take a look at Flagger deployment strategies.
[src:flux-cd/flux-get-started] This tutorial shows you how to bootstrap Flux to a Kubernetes cluster and deploy a sample application in a GitOps manner.
[src:flux-cd/flux-get-started] Note that for production use, it is recommended to have a dedicated GitHub account for Flux and use fine-grained access tokens with the minimum required permissions.
[src:flux-cd/flux-get-started] The `flux` command-line interface (CLI) is used to bootstrap and interact with Flux.
[src:flux-cd/flux-get-started] For other installation methods, see the CLI install documentation.
[src:flux-cd/flux-get-started] For information on how to bootstrap using a GitHub org, Gitlab and other git providers, see Bootstrapping.
[src:flux-cd/flux-get-started] This example uses a public repository github.com/stefanprodan/podinfo, podinfo is a tiny web application made with Go.
[src:flux-cd/flux-get-started] Configure Flux to build and apply the kustomize directory located in the podinfo repository.
[src:flux-cd/flux-get-started] Changes made to the podinfo Kubernetes manifests in the master branch are reflected in your cluster.
[src:flux-cd/flux-get-started] When a Kubernetes manifest is removed from the podinfo repository, Flux removes it from your cluster.
[src:flux-cd/flux-get-started] When you delete a `Kustomization` from the `fleet-infra` repository, Flux removes all Kubernetes objects previously applied from that `Kustomization`.
[src:flux-cd/flux-get-started] When you alter the podinfo deployment using `kubectl edit`, the changes are reverted to match the state described in Git.
[src:flux-cd/flux-get-started] Suspending updates to a kustomization allows you to directly edit objects applied from a kustomization, without your changes being reverted by the state in Git.
[src:flux-cd/flux-get-started] To suspend updates for a kustomization, run the command `flux suspend kustomization <name>`.
[src:flux-cd/flux-get-started] To resume updates run the command `flux resume kustomization <name>`.
[src:flux-cd/flux-get-started] To customize a deployment from a repository you don’t control, you can use Flux in-line patches.
[src:flux-cd/flux-get-started] The following example shows how to use in-line patches to change the podinfo deployment.
[src:flux-cd/flux-get-started] After the synchronization finishes, running `kubectl get pods` should display 3 pods.
[src:flux-cd/flux-get-started] To use Flux to manage more than one cluster or promote deployments from staging to production, take a look at the two approaches in the repositories listed below.
[src:flux-cd/flux] Open and extensible continuous delivery solution for Kubernetes.
[src:flux-cd/flux] Flux is a tool for keeping Kubernetes clusters in sync with sources of configuration (like Git repositories), and automating updates to configuration when there is new code to deploy.
[src:flux-cd/flux] Flux is built from the ground up to use Kubernetes' API extension system, and to integrate with Prometheus and other core components of the Kubernetes ecosystem.
[src:flux-cd/flux] Flux supports multi-tenancy and support for syncing an arbitrary number of Git repositories.
[src:flux-cd/flux] If you want to find out more about Flux UIs, check out our dedicated section.
[src:flux-cd/flux] Flux is based on a set of Kubernetes API extensions (“custom resources”), which control how git repositories and other sources of configuration are applied into the cluster (“synced”).
[src:flux-cd/flux] For example, you create a `GitRepository` object to mirror configuration from a Git repository, then a `Kustomization` object to sync that configuration.
[src:flux-cd/flux] Flux works with Kubernetes’ role-based access control (RBAC), so you can lock down what any particular sync can change.
[src:flux-cd/flux] It can send notifications to Slack and other like systems when configuration is synced and ready, and receive webhooks to tell it when to sync.
[src:flux-cd/flux] The `flux` command-line tool is a convenient way to bootstrap the system in a cluster, and to access the custom resources that make up the API.
[src:flux-cd/flux] CLI and running a couple of very simple commands, you will have a GitOps workflow setup which involves a staging and a production cluster.
[src:flux-cd/flux] If you should need help, please refer to our **Support page**.
[src:flux-cd/flux] for building Continuous Delivery on top of Kubernetes.
[src:flux-cd/flux] The GitOps Toolkit can be used individually by **platform engineers** who want to make their own continuous delivery system, and have requirements not covered by Flux.
[src:flux-cd/flux] The Flux project is always looking for new contributors and there are a multitude of ways to get involved.
[src:flux-cd/flux] Check out our **events calendar**, both with upcoming talks you can attend or past events videos you can watch.
